<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-5-2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Applications to Initial Value Problems</title>
<introduction>

  <p>
    As point out earlier in <xref ref="sec-5-1" />, we will need to convert a linear initial value problem into an algebraic equation using the Laplace transform.
    After solving the equation in the <m>s-</m>domain for the Laplace transform of the solution function, we then apply the inverse Laplace transform operator <m>\mathcal  {L}^{-1}</m> to return to the <m>t-</m>domain and obtain the solution of the initial value problem.
    For these steps, we will need the Laplace transform of derivatives.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-exponential-order-function" alt="exponential order function">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A function  <m>y(t)</m> defined on <m>[0,\infty)</m> is said to
        be of an exponential order as <m>t\to\infty</m> if there exists
        constants <m>\alpha</m>, <m>M\gt 0</m> and <m>t_0\ge 0</m> such that
        <me>
          |y(t)| \le M e^{\alpha t}\quad \text{for all } t\ge t_0.
        </me>
        The number <m>\alpha</m> is referred to as an <em><term>exponential order</term></em> of <m>y</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
     Then, for <m>
    s\gt \alpha,</m> we have
    <me>
      |y(t) e^{-st}|\le M e^{-(s-\alpha)t} \quad \text{for all }t\ge t_0,
    </me>
    and consequently,
    <me>
      \lim\limits_{t\to\infty}y(t) e^{-st} =0\quad \text{for }s&gt;\alpha.
    </me>
    </p>
</introduction>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Laplace-Transform-of-Derivatives">
        <title>Laplace Transforms of Derivatives</title>
<p>
    Suppose that <m>y'</m> is piecewise continuous on <m>[0,\infty)</m>
    and of an exponential order as <m>t\to\infty</m>. Assume that <m>\mathcal {L}\{y(t)\}</m> exists.
    Then, using integration by parts, we have
    <md>
      <mrow> \mathcal  {L}\{y'(t)\} \amp = \int_0^{\infty} e^{-st} y'(t) \, dt </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \left[ e^{-st} y(t) \right]_0^{\infty} + s \int_0^{\infty} e^{-st} y(t) \, dt</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =  -y(0) + s\mathcal  {L}\{y(t)\}</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = sY(s) - y(0)</mrow>
    </md>
    for <m>s&gt;\alpha.</m> Thus,
    <men xml:id="eq-5-2-1">
      \boxed{ \mathcal  {L}\{y'(t)\} = sY(s) - y(0).}
    </men>
  </p>

  <p>
    We extend the above idea to higher order derivatives.
    For instance, suppose that <m>y(t)</m> and <m>y'(t)</m> are continuous and of exponential order.
    If <m>y''(t)</m> exists and is piecewise continuous on <m>[0, \infty),</m>
    then applying the formula <xref ref="eq-5-2-1" /> first to <m>z'(t)</m> with <m>z(t) = y'(t)</m>
    and then to <m>y'(t)</m>, we obtain
    <md>
      <mrow>\mathcal  {L}\{y''(t)\}\amp =\mathcal  {L}\{z'(t)\} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = sZ(s) - z(0) </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp= s\mathcal  {L}\{y'(t)\}- y'(0)  </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = s(sY(s) - y(0)) - y'(0) </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp   =s^2Y(s) - sy(0)-y'(0),</mrow>
    </md>
    i.e.,
    <men xml:id="eq-5-2-2">
      \boxed{\mathcal  {L}\{y''(t)\} = s^2Y(s) - sy(0)-y'(0).}
    </men>
  </p>

  <p>
    Applying these ideas repeatedly to higher order derivatives, we obtain the following theorem whose proof is omitted.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-5-2-1" alt="Laplace transform of derivatives">
    <title>(Laplace transform of derivatives)</title>

    <p>
      Let <m>n\ge 1</m> be a positive integer.
      If <m>y, y', \ldots, y^{(n-1)}</m> are continuous on <m>[0, \infty)</m> and of exponential order as <m>t\to\infty</m> and if <m>y^{(n)}(t)</m> is piecewise continuous on <m>[0, \infty)</m> and of exponential order as <m>t\to\infty,</m> then
      <me>
        \mathcal  {L}\{y^{(n)}(t)\} = s^n Y(s) - s^{n-1}y(0) - s^{n-2}y'(0) - \cdots - y^{(n-1)}(0),
      </me>
      where <m>Y(s) = \mathcal  {L}\{y(t)\}</m>.
    </p>
  </theorem>

  <p>
    <xref ref="thm-5-2-1" /> presents how <m>y(0),y'(0), \dots, y^{(n-1)}(0)</m> naturally arise, reflecting the initial conditions of an <m>n</m>-th order linear initial value problem and indicating the potential use of the Laplace transform to covert a linear differential equation with constant coefficients to an algebraic equation with no derivatives of the Laplace transform of the solution variable. Specifically, consider the linear initial value problem of the form:
    <men xml:id="eq-5-2-3">
      \begin{cases} &amp;a_n y^{(n)} + a_{n-1}y^{(n-1)}+ \cdots+a_1y'+a_0 y = f(t),\\ &amp;y(0) = y_0, \dots, y^{(n-1)}(0)= y_{n-1}.
      \end{cases}
    </men>
    Applying <xref ref="thm-5-2-1" /> in conjunction with the linearity of <m>\mathcal  {L}</m>, the initial value problem in <xref ref="eq-5-2-3" /> gives rise to the following algebraic equation in the <m>s-</m>domain:
    <men xml:id="eq-5-2-4">
      <mrow>&amp;a_n\big(s^n Y(s) - s^{n-1}y(0) - s^{n-2}y'(0) - \cdots - y^{(n-1)}(0)\big)</mrow>
      <mrow>&amp;+a_{n-1}\big(s^{n-1} Y(s) - s^{n-2}y(0) - s^{n-3}y'(0) - \cdots - y^{(n-2)}(0)\big)</mrow>
      <mrow>&amp;\vdots</mrow>
      <mrow>&amp;+a_1\big(sY(s)- y(0)\big) + a_0Y(s)= F(s),</mrow>
    </men>
    which takes the form
    <men xml:id="eq-5-2-5">
      p(s)Y(s)= q(s) +F(s),
    </men>
    where <m>p(s) = a_ns^n+a_{n-1}s^{n-1} + \cdots+ a_1s+a_0</m> and <m>q(s)</m> is a polynomial in <m>s</m> obtained from all the remaining terms on the left side of the equation <xref ref="eq-5-2-5" />.
    It then follows that
    <men xml:id="eq-5-2-6">
      Y(s)= \frac{q(s)}{p(s)} +\frac{F(s)}{p(s)}.
    </men>
    The solution <m>y(t)</m> to the initial value problem (<xref ref="eq-5-2-3" />) is given by
    <men xml:id="eq-5-2-7">
      y(t) = \mathcal  {L}^{-1}\{Y(s)\} =\mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{q(s)}{p(s)}\right\} +\mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{F(s)}{p(s)}\right\}.
    </men>
    To find
    <md>
      \mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{q(s)}{p(s)}\right\} \quad\text{and}\quad\mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{F(s)}{p(s)}\right\},
    </md>
    we typically use partial fraction decomposition of <m>{q(s)}/{p(s)}</m> and <m>{F(s)}/{p(s)}</m> and then use appropriate inverse Laplace transforms term by term.
    For more details on the techniques of partial fraction decomposition, see Appendix <xref ref="partial-fraction-decomposition" />.
  </p>

  <p>
    In principle, one should verify that the equation <xref ref="eq-5-2-7" /> satisfies the initial value problem <xref ref="eq-5-2-3" /> by verifying that <m>y(t)</m> solves the differential equation and satisfies the initial conditions, especially important when the differential equation is defined also for <m>t &lt; 0</m> since the Laplace transform only makes sense to functions on <m>[0, \infty)</m>.
    However, this verification is unnecessary when <m>f(t)</m> is continuous on an open interval containing <m>t = 0</m>, as the initial value problem <xref ref="eq-5-2-3" /> is guaranteed to have a unique local solution.
  </p>

  <p>
    In the following examples, we apply the Laplace transform method to solve initial value problems.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="ex-5-2-1">
    <p>
      Solve the initial value problem using the Laplace transform:
      <md>
        y'-y= 2\cos(3t), \quad y(0) = 1.
      </md>
    </p>

    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>y(t)=\frac{6}{5}e^t-\frac{1}{5}\cos(3t)+\frac{3}{5}\sin(3t)</m> on <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>.
      </p>
    </answer>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Applying the Laplace transform to both sides of the equation, we have
        <md>
          \begin{aligned} \mathcal  {L}\{y'\} - \mathcal  {L}\{y\} &amp;= 2\mathcal  {L}\{\cos(3t)\} \\ (sY(s) - y(0)) - Y(s) &amp;= 2\cdot \frac{s}{s^2 + 9} \\ (s-1)Y(s) &amp;= 1 + \frac{2s}{s^2 + 9} \\ Y(s) &amp;= \frac{1}{s-1} + \frac{2s}{(s-1)(s^2 + 9)}.
          \end{aligned}
        </md>
        To find the inverse Laplace transform of <m>{2s}/{((s-1)(s^2 + 9))}</m>, we use partial fraction decomposition to write
        <md>
          \frac{2s}{(s-1)(s^2 + 9)} = \frac{A}{s-1} + \frac{Bs + C}{s^2 + 9}.
        </md>
        Solving for <m>A, B, C</m>, we have <m>A = 1/5, B = -1/5, C = 9/5.</m> Thus,
        <md>
          \begin{aligned} Y(s) &amp;= \frac{1}{s-1} + \frac{1/5}{s-1} + \frac{-1/5 s + 9  /5}{s^2 + 9} \\ &amp;= \frac{6/5}{s-1} + \frac{-1/5 s + 9/5}{s^2 + 9}.
          \end{aligned}
        </md>
        Applying the inverse Laplace transform term by term, we have
        <md>
          \begin{aligned}y(t) &amp;= \mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{6/5}{s-1}\right\} + \mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{-1/5 s + 9/5}{s^2 + 9}\right\} \\ &amp;= \frac{6}{5}e^t - \frac{1}{5}\cos(3t) + \frac{3}{5}\sin(3t).
          \end{aligned}
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="ex-5-2-2">
    <p>
      Solve the initial value problem using the Laplace transform:
      <me>
        y''-5y'+4y= t, \quad y(0) = 1, y'(0) = 0.
      </me>
    </p>

    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>y(t)=e^t-\dfrac{5}{16}e^{4t}+\dfrac14 t+\dfrac{5}{16}</m> on <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>.
      </p>
    </answer>

    <solution>
      Applying the Laplace transform to both sides of the equation, we have
      <md>
        \begin{aligned}&amp;\mathcal  {L}\{y''\} - 5\mathcal  {L}\{y'\} + 4\mathcal  {L}\{y\} = \mathcal  {L}\{t\} \\ &amp;(s^2 Y(s) - sy(0)-y'(0)) - 5(sY(s) - y(0)) + 4Y(s) = \frac{1}{s^2} \\ &amp;(s^2 - 5s + 4)Y(s) = \frac{1}{s^2} + s - 5 \\ &amp;Y(s) = \frac{1}{s^2(s-1)(s-4)} + \frac{s-5}{(s-1)(s-4)}=\frac{s^3-5s^2+1}{s^2(s-1)(s-4)}.
        \end{aligned}
      </md>

      <p>
        Decompose into partial fractions:
      </p>
      <md>
        \frac{s^3-5s^2+1}{s^2(s-1)(s-4)} =\frac{A}{s}+\frac{B}{s^2}+\frac{C}{s-1}+\frac{D}{s-4}.
      </md>

      <p>
        Solving for the constants gives
      </p>
      <md>
        A=\frac{5}{16},\qquad B=\frac{1}{4},\qquad C=1,\qquad D=-\frac{5}{16}.
      </md>

      <p>
        Hence
      </p>
      <md>
        Y(s)=\frac{5}{16s}+\frac{1}{4s^2}+\frac{1}{s-1}-\frac{5}{16(s-4)}.
      </md>

      <p>
        Now apply the inverse Laplace transform:
      </p>

      <p>
        Therefore,
        <md>
          \begin{aligned} y(t)\amp =\mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{5}{16s}\right\}+ \mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{4s^2}\right\}\\ \amp +\mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s-1}\right\} -\mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{5}{16(s-4)}\right\}\\ \amp =\frac{5}{16}+\frac{1}{4}t+e^t-\frac{5}{16}e^{4t}.
          \end{aligned}
        </md>
        We can show that
        <md>
          y(t)=\frac{5}{16}+\frac{1}{4}t+e^t-\frac{5}{16}e^{4t} \quad \text{ on } (-\infty, \infty)
        </md>
        is the solution of  the initial value problem on by verifying that it satisfies the differential equation and the initial conditions.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="ex-5-2-3">
    <title>Move this to a later section</title>

    Solve the initial value problem using the Laplace transform:
    <me>
      y'' + 4y' + 5y = e^{-t}, \quad y(0) = 0, \; y'(0) = 2.
    </me>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Applying the Laplace transform to both sides of the equation, we have
        <me>
          \begin{aligned} &amp;\mathcal  {L}\{y''\} + 4\mathcal  {L}\{y'\} + 5\mathcal  {L}\{y\}     = \mathcal  {L}\{e^{-t}\} \\ &amp;(s^2 Y(s) - sy(0) - y'(0)) + 4          (sY(s) - y(0)) + 5Y(s) = \frac{1}{s+1} \\ &amp;(s^2 + 4s + 5)Y(s) = \frac{1}{s+1} + 2 \\ &amp;Y(s) = \frac{1}{(s+1)(s^2 + 4s + 5)} + \frac{2}{s^2 + 4s + 5}.
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
        To find the inverse Laplace transform of <m>{1}/{((s+1)(s^2 + 4s + 5))}</m>, we use partial fraction decomposition to write
        <me>
          \frac{1}{(s+1)(s^2 + 4s + 5)} = \frac{A}{s+1} + \frac{Bs + C}{s^2 + 4s + 5}.
        </me>
        Solving for <m>A, B, C</m>, we have <m>A = 1/5, B = -1/5, C = 1/5.</m> Thus,
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}Y(s) &amp;= \frac{1/5}{s+1} + \frac{-1/5 s + 1/5}{s^2 + 4s + 5} + \frac{2}{s^2 + 4s + 5} \\ &amp;= \frac{1/5}{s+1} + \frac{-1/5 s + 11/5}{s^2 + 4s + 5}.
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
        Applying the inverse Laplace transform term by term, we have
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}y(t) &amp;= \mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1/5}{s+1}\right\} + \mathcal  {L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{-1/5 s + 11/5}{s^2 + 4s + 5}\right\} \\ &amp;= \frac{1}{5}e^{-t} - \frac{1}{5}e^{-2t}\cos(t) + \frac{9}{5}e^{-2t}\sin(t).
          \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
  </subsection>
  <statement>
      <p>
    The general principle for solving initial value problems by the Laplace transform method remains the same as demonstrated in the previous examples.
    The major effort to make is in computing the Laplace transforms of more complicated functions and finding inverse transforms of more complicated expressions.
    In the followings sections, we continue exploring additional methods for computing Laplace transforms and solve initial value problems that involve more complicated functions.
  </p>
  </statement>


  <exercises xml:id="exercises-5-2">
  <exercise>
    <p>
      Solve the following initial value problems using the Laplace transform method:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol marker ="i.">
        <li>
          <m>y' - y =1, \quad y(0) = 0</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m>y'-6y = e^{2t}, \quad y(0) = 1</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m>y'' +5y+6y = e^{2t}, \quad y(0) = 0, \; y'(0) = 0</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m>y'' -5y' + 6y = e^{2t}, \quad y(0) = 1, \; y'(0) = 0</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m>y'' + 9y = e^{2t}, \quad y(0) = 0, \; y'(0) = 1</m>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <exercises>
  <exercise xml:id="ex-first">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Solve <m>x^2-5x+6=0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>x=2</m> or <m>x=3</m>.
      </p>
    </answer>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Factor:
        <me>
          (x-2)(x-3)=0
        </me>
        so the solutions are <m>x=2</m> and <m>x=3</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>
  </exercises> -->

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Solve the following initial value problems using the Laplace transform method:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol marker ="i.">
        <li>
          <m>y'+y = e^{3t}\sin(2t), \quad y(0) = 0</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m>y''-4y'+5y = 0, \quad y(0) = 0,\; y'(0) =1</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m>y''-y'= e^t \sin t\quad y(0) =0,\; y'(0) =0</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m>y'''+2y''-y'-2y = \sin t, \quad y(0)= 0,\; y'(0)= 0,\; y''(0) =1</m>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Solve the following initial value problems using the Laplace transform method:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol marker ="i.">
        <li>
          <m>y'+4y = f(t), \quad y(0) = 0,</m> where <m>f(t) =\begin{cases} 1 &amp;\text{ if } 0\le t &lt;1\\ -1&amp;\text{ if } t \ge 1 \end{cases}</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m>y'+4y = f(t), \quad y(0) = 0,</m> where <m>f(t) =\begin{cases} \sin t&amp;\text{ if } 0\le t &lt;1\\ 0&amp;\text{ if } t\ge 1 \end{cases}</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m>y''-y'= \cos t\; \mathcal  {U}(t-2\pi)\quad y(0) =1,\; y'(0) =1</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m>y''+5y'+6y = \mathcal  {U}(t-2\pi), \quad y(0)= 0,\; y'(0)= 1</m>
        </li>

        <li>
          <m> y''+4y'+3y = 1- \mathcal  {U}(t-2) - \mathcal  {U}(t-4),\; y(0) = 0,\; y'(0) = 0</m>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </exercise>
  </exercises>
</section>